          section#apostrophe.c-Document__Released(data-status="released")
            h3 The Apostrophe
            p.
              Normal and efficient typing would dictate that apostrophes, in both possessive
              nouns and contractions, use the apostrophe key on the keyboard (next to the
              #[kbd: kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key return] key). However, in very formal documents, such as those
              presented to peers or those soon to be published (in a blog, for example), authors are
              encouraged to use the #[b right single-quote] entity
              (#[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &#x005d;]]
              or #[code &amp;rsquo;]) as it is more typographically appropriate. See the
              examples below for differences in rendering.
            figure.crossgrid-lined.
              The word #[i(class="!fs:i") I&apos;m] is a contraction with a regular apostrophe,
              while the word #[i(class="!fs:i") Cody&rsquo;s] is a possessive noun that uses the right
              single-quote character. Notice the difference in characters.
            p.
              Use the regular apostrophe character (#[kbd: kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &apos;]) in
              non-normative documents, drafts, #[i(lang="la"): abbr(title="et cetera") etc.]
              Also use it in code as another type of string
              delimiter. The #[code &amp;apos;] entity in HTML should only be used to escape
              the apostrophe character in an example of code.
            figure
              figcaption.c-Caption.
                The following snippet of HTML instructs authors how to
                use apostrophes in JavaScript code.
              pre.
                &lt;p&gt; To get a pop-up, call
                &lt;code&gt; alert( #[u &amp;apos;] Hello, world. #[u &amp;apos;] ); &lt;/code&gt;
                in the event. &lt;/p&gt;
        ins(class="!d:bk !pl:0" datetime="2015-07-30 16:26")
          section#apostrphe.c-Document__Draft(data-status="draft")
            h3 The Apostrophe
            section
              h4 Usage
              p.
                There is much debate on the correct use of the apostrophe. For brevity in this post,
                let it be a blanket rule that apostrophes shall be used only for contractions and
                possessive nouns, and they shall not be used for plurals.
                The following examples demonstrate correct usage according to these specifications.
              dl
                dt they&rsquo;re
                dd contraction of &ldquo;they&rdquo; and &ldquo;are&rdquo;
                dt the robot&rsquo;s room
                dd the room that belongs to the robot
                dt the robots&rsquo; room
                dd.
                  the room that belongs to all the robots
                  (there is no #[i s] after the apostrophe because there is already an added #[i s] in the plural of #[i robot])
                dt the child&rsquo;s room
                dd the room that belongs to the child
                dt the children&rsquo;s room
                dd.
                  the room that belongs to all the children
                  (there #[em is] an #[i s] after the apostrophe because there is no #[i s] in the plural of #[i child])
                dt Glados&rsquo;s voice
                dd.
                  the voice belongs to Glados
                  (there #[em is] an #[i s] after the apostrophe because the #[i s] in #[i Glados] is not added: it&rsquo;s part of the name)
                dt the #[abbr(title="Aperture Science Enrichment Center") ASEC]&rsquo;s testing facility
                dd the testing facility that belongs to the #[abbr(title="Aperture Science Enrichment Center") ASEC]
                dt the #[abbr(title="Aperture Science Enrichment Center") ASEC]s
                dd plural of the abbreviation #[i: abbr(title="Aperture Science Enrichment Center") ASEC]
                dt born in the &rsquo;80s
                dd contraction of #[i 1980s] (plural)
              p.o-Box.o-Box--island.c-Alert.c-Alert--info.
                #[strong.c-Alert__Title Note:]
                There is one case in which apostrophes may be used to indicate plurals:
                when the author is referring to the plural of a single, lower-case letter.
                However there are alternatives to this exception, which are preferable.
              figure
                p Dot your i&rsquo;s, cross your t&rsquo;s, and mind your p&rsquo;s and q&rsquo;s.
                p Dot your Is, cross your Ts, and mind your Ps and Qs.
                p Dot your #[i i]s, cross your #[i t]s, and mind your #[i p]s and #[i q]s.
                figcaption.
                  The last paragraph is the best alternative as it
                  #[a(rel="this" href="#scare-mention") uses the #[code i] Element to mention] the letters.
            section
              h4 Encoding
              p.
                Normal and efficient typing would dictate that apostrophes be encoded with
                #[b U+0027 Apostrophe (&apos;)], accessed by the #[b.o-Textbox.c-Key &apos;] key
                on the keyboard (next to the #[b.o-Textbox.c-Key return] key). Use this character in
                non-normative documents, drafts, emails, texts, #[i(lang="la"): abbr(title="et cetera") etc.]
                Also use it in code as another type of string delimiter, for example, to mark up a string
                within another string already delimited by #[a(rel="this" href="#quotes") quotation marks]. The
                #[code &amp;apos;] entity in HTML should only be used to escape
                the apostrophe character in an example of code.
              figure
                figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--before.
                  The following is a snippet showing a string inside an HTML attribute.
                pre &lt;button onclick=&quot;alert(#[u &apos;]Hello, world.#[u &apos;])&quot;&gt; click me &lt;/button&gt;
              figure
                figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--before.
                  The following is a snippet of HTML instructing how to use apostrophes in JavaScript code.
                pre.
                  &lt;p&gt; To get a pop-up, put
                    &lt;code&gt; alert(#[u &amp;apos;]Hello, world.#[u &amp;apos;]); &lt;/code&gt;
                    in the &lt;code&gt; onclick &lt;/code&gt; attribute. &lt;/p&gt;
              p.
                In very formal documents, such as those presented to peers or those soon to be published
                (in a blog, for example), authors are encouraged to use
                #[b U+2019 Right Single Quotation Mark (&rsquo;)]
                (#[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &#x005d;]]
                or #[code &amp;rsquo;]) as it is more typographically appropriate.
                This has been the consensus of the Unicode committee, but
                #[a(href="https://tedclancy.wordpress.com/2015/06/03/which-unicode-character-should-represent-the-english-apostrophe-and-why-the-unicode-committee-is-very-wrong/") opponents have been slowly gaining support].
              p.
                The prevailing argument is that since #[b U+2019] is technically a punctuation mark, which
                separates words, contractions and possessions are incorrectly interpreted as two separate
                words. This is simply not the case: the word #[i doesn&rsquo;t] is not two words
                #[i doesn] and #[i t], it&rsquo;s one single word
                (albeit a contraction of the two words #[i does] and #[i not]).
                Instead of using a punctuation mark, we should be using
                a letter-like symbol because it becomes part of the word.
              p.
                Perhaps a more convincing argument is that a right single quotation mark used as an
                apostrophe #[em does not have an opening quotation mark]. This causes problems in many
                text editors that pair delimiters, and word processors that have the ability to select text
                word-by-word. In the latter case, for example, double-clicking the #[i o] in
                #[i doesn&rsquo;t] would select #[i doesn], not the entire word. This is because the word
                treats the right single quotation mark as the end of a quoted phrase.
              p.
                Opponents submit that the correct encoding should be #[b U+02BC Modifier Letter Apostrophe (&#x02bc;)],
                which appears identical to the right single quotation mark.
              p.
                It is difficult to gain support, though.
                The Unicode committee says this character should be reserved for apostrophes representing
                modifier letters,
                #[a(cite="http://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode7.0.0/ch06.pdf") for example, in transliterations to indicate a glottal stop].
                Furthermore, there is simply no
                easy keyboard shortcut for this character, and no HTML entity shorthand name. To mark it up,
                one must type #[code &amp;#x02bc;].
              figure.crossgrid-lined.
                The word #[i I&apos;m] is a contraction with a regular Apostrophe,
                while the word #[i Cody&rsquo;s] is a possessive noun that uses the
                Right Single Quotation Mark. The Modifier Letter Apostrophe, which does not break words
                but rather is treated as part of a word, is shown in the possessive plural
                #[i children&#x02bc;s].
              p.
                It is this author&rsquo;s opinion that there must be some middle ground. The
                #[b U+2019] is too far to the left, as the apostrophe is not used for
                quoting material, but the #[b U+02BC] is too far to the right, as the
                apostrophe is not used as a letter of the alphabet or to indicate pronounciation.
                I think there should be a third option&mdash;dare I suggest it be named the
                #[i Punctuation Apostrophe]&mdash;but perhaps it will be a very long time until the Unicode
                committee decides on a solution.
              p.
                For the time being, we must stick to the convention they have prescribed.
                #[strong Use #[b U+2019 Right Single Quotation Mark] for apostrophes in contractions and possessions.]
        section#quotes.c-Document__Released(data-status="released")
          h3 The Quotation Mark
          p.
            The #[b quotation mark] has many uses.
            Most people use it in plain text (think email, #[i(lang="la") circa] #[time 1996]) to
            show emphasis or importance,
            indicate a change in tone or voice,
            mark up an idiomatic expression or phrase, or
            highlight key words.
            When text formatting isn&rsquo;t available, people have to revert to
            punctuation to semantically mark up elements&mdash;the whole point of this article.
          p.
            In a quick-and-dirty setting such as one listed above, use the
            normal quotation mark character by typing
            #[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &apos;]].
            This produces an #[i ambidexterous] quotation mark and doesn&rsquo;t look too pretty
            from a typographical point of view.
          p.
            In formal documents such as technical reports and blog posts,
            use proper #[b left and right double-quote] entities
            (#[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &#x005b;]] and
            #[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &#x005b;]],
            or #[code &amp;ldquo;] and #[code &amp;rdquo;])
            when you need to surround a phrase with quotation marks, for whatever reason.
          figure.crossgrid-lined
            p &quot;This sentence is surrounded with ambidexterous quotation mark characters.&quot;
            p &ldquo;This sentence is surrounded with the left double and right double quotation mark characters.&rdquo;
          p.
            In most cases though, these entities will not be needed. In the case of an
            actual quotation (spoken by a person, fictional or not), use the #[code q] Element,
            possibly with the #[code [cite]] attribute. In the case of
            #[a(rel="this" href="#scare-mention") scare quotes and mentions],
            use the #[code i] Element with appropriate CSS.
          p.
            There is one more thing worth mentioning: if you must #[b escape] the
            quotation mark character, the HTML entity is #[code &amp;quot;]. Use this only
            when demonstrating code in an example or figure. Otherwise, just use the
            normal quotation mark character.
