        section#colon.c-Document__Complete(data-status="complete")
          h3 The Colon
          p A colon separates a complete sentence and a list or example. See the figure below.
          figure.crossgrid-lined
            p The following sentence is correct: #[q I have two favorite hobbies: reading and writing.]
            p An incorrect usage would be: #[q My two favorite hobbies are: reading and writing.]
          p In general, a colon can almost always be replaced with the word #[i namely].
          p.
            A colon usually precedes a list or some sort of enumeration, either
            implicitly (in prose) or explicitly (via an actual bulleted or numbered list). Colons
            can also precede an example or illustration. See the introduction of each example above.
          p.
            The first letter of the first word following a colon is usually not capitalized.
            There are two exceptions: if the list items in a bulleted list that follow are capitalized,
            and if the colon separates a title and subtitle of, for example, a book.
        section#emdash.c-Document__Complete(data-status="complete")
          h3 The Dash
          p.
            When unspecified, the word #[i dash] almost always refers to the
            #[b em dash]
            (#[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key -]] or #[code &amp;mdash;] in HTML).
          p.
            The single dash, like the colon, can be used to indicate a pause or
            interruption in prose. However, dashes are stronger and more informal than colons.
          figure.crossgrid-lined I have two hobbies: cooking and cleaning.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after This example could be read,  #[q I have two hobbies, and I&rsquo;m going to tell you what they are. Cooking and cleaning.]
          figure.crossgrid-lined I have two hobbies&mdash;cooking and cleaning.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after This one could be read, #[q I have two hobbies. Wait for it, wait for it. Cooking and cleaning!] This is not a good use of the em dash.
          figure.crossgrid-lined When we boarded the plane, we realized we only forgot one thing&mdash;the baby.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after This is a more appropriate use of the em dash.
          p.
            Don&rsquo;t use dashes for the boring or mundane. Dashes are dramatic. Also,
            notice the lack of spaces surrounding the dash. This is the common practice.
          p.
            Dashes are not hyphens. Hyphens (found next to the #[kbd: kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key 0])
            are used for compound words and a bunch of other stuff that I&rsquo;m not really sure
            about. But they don&rsquo;t indicate pauses. The same goes for #[b en dashes]
            (#[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key -]] or #[code &amp;ndash;]).
            En dashes indicate an inclusive range of numbers and could be replaced by the
            word #[i to].
        section#semicolon.c-Document__Complete(data-status="complete")
          h3 The Semicolon
          p.
            Use a semicolon to combine two closely related clauses: clauses that are too
            close to be separate sentences. There should be a complete clause on each side of the
            semicolon, and there should not be a conjunction immediately following the semicolon.
            A correct usage followed by an incorrect usage is shown below.
          figure.crossgrid-lined Nationally, the ratio is about 800 students per administrator; Maine is about 400 to 1, suggesting a waste of funds.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after.
              The first and second clauses are sufficiently closely related that they
              should be in the same sentence.
          figure.crossgrid-lined The national ratio of students to administrators is about 800 to 1; however in Maine the ratio is lower, suggesting a waste of funds.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after.
              In this example, the semicolon should be replaced with a comma or a period.
          p.
            Semicolons are also sometimes used to separate phrases that may contain smaller
            phrases with commas. In this case, using commas to separate big list items as well as
            smaller list items is too confusing, so the semicolon makes a distinction.
          figure.crossgrid-lined Your essay should contain five paragraphs: an introduction, which contains a thesis statement and establishes three points; three body paragraphs, one for each point; and a conclusion, or summary.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after.
              The directions contain three list items, but each list item contains
              non-restrictive clauses, which use commas. Thus semicolons are used to separate
              the list items.
        section#ellipsis.c-Document__Complete(data-status="complete")
          h3 The Ellipsis
          p.
            Contrary to its appearance, the ellipsis is one character. It is not three periods
            in a row, nor is it three periods separated by spaces. The
            ellipsis#[sup: a#rf-ellipses.Rf(rel="this" href="#fn-ellipses") 1]
            can be accessed
            via #[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key ;]], or the character
            entity #[code &amp;hellip;] in HTML. It is convention to insert a single space before and
            after each ellipsis, therefore treating it as a normal word or group of words.
          p.
            There are two main uses of the ellipsis. The first, which
            may be used in formal writing, is within quoted material. (In HTML, direct quotes should be
            contained in a #[code q] Element or #[code blockquote] Element, depending on a number
            of variables.) Within a directly-quoted passage, an ellipsis indicates an omission of material
            that was present in the original quotation, but removed in the written reproduction for various
            purposes. These reasons might include making the reproduction more consise or more understandable.
            In any case, the quote must maintain grammatical sense and it must maintain its original semantics.
          p.
            The second use of the ellipsis is more informal than the first, and as such, the
            rules for using it are much less strict. In informal writing (such as emails or text messages),
            the ellipsis may be used to indicate a pause or break in the writer&rsquo;s train of
            thought&mdash;much like a dash. In contrast with the dash, though, the ellipsis indicates a stronger
            or longer pause, which might be
            #[q(cite="http://grammar.quickanddirtytips.com/chicago-style.aspx") accompanied by confusion, insecurity, distress, or uncertainty.]
            #[q(cite="http://www.quickanddirtytips.com/education/grammar/ellipses?page=1") Dashes &hellip; should be reserved for more &hellip; decisive pauses.]
            One final contrast is that the dash
            should not be surrounded by spaces, while the ellipsis should.
          footer
            ul.c-ListFootnotes
              li.
                #[sup: a#fn-ellipses.Fn(rel="this" href="#rf-ellipses") 1]
                The plural form of a singular ellipsis is #[i ellipses], not to be confused with the homonyn
                #[a(rel="external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse") #[i ellipses], a set of closed conic sections].
      section#punct-phrases.c-Document__Complete(data-status="complete")
        h2 Separated Phrases
        section#parens
          h3 Parentheses
          p.
            A single open parenthesis begins an aside and is always paired with a closing
            parenthesis. Together, these two parentheses separate the aside from the surrounding prose.
          p.
            The phrase inside the parentheses is extraneous information (which means it
            could be removed without disrupting the flow of prose or changing its meaning). The
            sentence you just read was a bad example of using parentheses because the remark inside
            was integral to the sentence (it explained what #[i extraneous information]
            meant). That last one was okay, though. When deciding whether to use parentheses,
            #[q Is this information a necessary part of the sentence?]
            If not, it&rsquo;s okay to place it in parentheses.
          figure.crossgrid-lined.
            They fled through the woods, and then found George (dear, sweet George
            the accountant) lying dead in the creek.
        section#emdash-phrase
          h3 Dashes: Part Two
          p.
            The em dash&mdash;apart from indicating a pause&mdash;can also be used with
            a twin to indicate asides. In contrast to parentheses, dashes are used to highlight
            a phrase and bring it to the reader&rsquo;s attention. Remember, dashes are dramatic.
            If the aside were removed, the sentence would convey a different mood because that
            information removed would no longer be worth any attention.
          p.
            The first sentence in the preceeding paragraph uses a pair of em dashes to
            highlight the fact that em dashes have another function: they may indicate a pause.
            Re-read the sentence without the aside
            (#[q(cite="#emdash-phrase") The em dash can also be used with a twin&hellip;])
            and see how the meaning changes.
          p.
            Again, the dashes should be adjacent to the words inside and out. There
            should be no immediate spaces or punctuation next to the dash.
          figure.crossgrid-lined.
            They fled through the woods, and then George&mdash;dear, sweet George
            the accountant&mdash;jumped out and stabbed them.
        section#comma2
          h3 Commas: Part Two
          p.
            There are just too many rules about commas, so I won&rsquo;t talk about
            them all. But below are a few examples of when commas can be used to separate a clause
            from a sentence.
          section
            h4 Appositives
            figure.crossgrid-lined.
              My first dog, Axel, was found astray.
            p.
              Axel&rsquo;s name is unnecessarily included because I can only have one
              first dog. Thus we surround his name with commas.
              His name and the commas may be removed without changing the
              sentence&rsquo;s semantics. A counterexample would be, #[q My dog Axel was found astray.]
              If I have more than one dog, I need to clarify which one was found astray
              in this case. I can&rsquo;t surround his name with commas.
          section
            h4 Nonrestrictive Clauses
            figure.crossgrid-lined.
              Diamonds, which are expensive, aren&rsquo;t something I buy often.
            p.
              All diamonds are expensive, so there&rsquo;s no need to indicate this in
              the sentence. The commas indicate the clause is unnecessary.
              Remove the phrase and commas and the meaning stays the same. On the
              other hand, #[i Diamonds that are found in the ocean are very rare] is not
              a nonrestrictive clause (it&rsquo;s a restrictive clause) because it distinguishes
              diamonds that are found in the ocean from other diamonds. We can&rsquo;t surround
              the clause #[q(cite="#comma2") that are found in the ocean] with commas.
            ins(class="!d:bk" datetime="2015-04-30 15:25")
              p.
                One general rule of thumb is that nonrestrictive causes (with commas) contain the word
                #[i which], and restrictive clauses (without commas) contain the word #[i that].
                Of course, this rule is very lax and there are many exceptions.
