        section#scare-mention
          h3 Scare Quotes and Mentions
          ins(class="!d:bk" datetime="2014-08-06 00:18")
            p.
              This section describes the use of an HTML Element, in particular,
              the #[code i] Element. As such, it no longer belongs in this document. It
              is here only for historical purposes.
          p.
            Mark up scare quotes and mentions with the
            #[del(datetime="2014-08-06 00:18") #[b left and right double-quote] entities (#[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &#x005b;]] and #[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key option] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key &#x005b;]], or #[code &amp;ldquo;] and #[code &amp;rdquo;])]
            #[ins(datetime="2014-08-06 00:18") #[code i] Element].
            Do not use the #[code q] Element.
            #[ins(datetime="2014-08-06 00:18") Continue reading for more information about scare quotes and mentions.]
          p.
            #[a(rel="external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scare_quotes"): dfn#d-scare-quote Scare quotes]
            are expressions that abuse
            vocabulary or language, sarcastic expressions, double entendres, metaphors or analogies,
            onomatopoeias, and other idioms of the like. In spoken language, people typically
            indicate scare quotes by making
            #[del(datetime="2015-02-04 11:27") the quote signs]
            #[ins(datetime="2015-02-04 11:27"): a(rel="external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_quotes") air quotes]:
            by holding their hands up and bending
            the first two fingers on each hand. If you would do this while speaking a word or phrase,
            it&rsquo;s most likely a scare quote.
          figure.crossgrid-lined.
            My hair is not #[i black;] it&rsquo;s just very dark brown.
          figure.crossgrid-lined.
            Yeah, I&rsquo;m #[i sorry] your cat found his way into my yard when the dog was hungry.
          p.
            A #[dfn#d-mention mention] refers to an explicit word or phrase
            without conveying meaning to the sentence. If the word or phrase could be replaced with
            nonsense and the sentence would still be syntactically correct, then it is a mention.
            However, if the word or phrase is integral to the meaning of the sentence, then
            #[a(rel="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Use%E2%80%93mention_distinction") it is not being #[em mentioned], but rather #[em used]].
          figure.crossgrid-lined Don&rsquo;t use #[i equals] when you mean #[i implies].
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after.
              In this example, the words #[i equals] and
              #[i implies] are #[em mentioned] because the author is referring to
              the actual words. They can be replaced with nonsense words and the sentence would
              still be syntactically correct.
          figure.crossgrid-lined
            p #[q Infection equals fever,] said Foreman.
            p Cameron corrected him.
              q.
                No, infection #[em implies] fever. She could still have a fever and not have an
                infection. It could be autoimmune.
            figcaption.c-Caption.c-Caption--after.
              The words #[i equals] and #[i implies] are #[em used] in this example.
          p.
            There is no specific markup for indicating used phrases since their semantics are
            already integral to the Element they are in.
            #[ins(datetime="2015-04-30 22:52") In the example above, the word #[i implies] is marked up with #[code &lt;em&gt;] only because Cameron used stress emphasis to correct Foreman.]
